A Dive into Autoencoders

Elvira Fleury and Rachel Slimovitch

5/8/2023

What are autoencoders?

An autoencoder is a type of neural network that learns efficient representations of the input data. In this post, we will explain traditional autoencoders, which use a feedforward network structure with the same number of nodes in the input and output layer. Note that there are variations such as recurrent or variational autoencoders that deviate from a purely feedforward neural network, but we will not discuss them in this post.

The role of the autoencoder is to use the hidden layers to try and re-create the inputs. There are two main parts of the autoencoder algorithm: the encoder function, which converts the inputs into codings in a hidden layer; and the decoder function, which reconstructs the inputs from the codings in the hidden layer. Autoencoders are unsupervised as they learn to reconstruct input without relying on explicit labels. The diagram below provides a schematic representation of the autoencoder architecture:

knitr::include_graphics("intro_image.png")

Autoencoders are typically trained with only one hidden layer as seen in the diagram above. However, they can have multiple hidden layers and are thus referred to as stacked or deep autoencoders. The additional depth allows the codings to take on more complex relationships but it is computationally expensive. In our project, we will demonstrate stacked autoencoders as our encoder and decoder have two hidden layers.

While the goal of our feedforward network is to be able to reconstruct the input data as best as possible (minimizing the difference between the input and output), we are often more interested in the layer between the encoder and decoder. This layer is referred to as the latent layer as it captures the underlying structure of the input data.Traditional autoencoders are undercomplete, meaning that the dimensionality of the inner representation is smaller than the input data. This latent layer is forced to capture the most dominant features of the input data.

We will use Not-MNIST data to explore different uses of autoencoders. The Not-MNIST dataset is a collection of over 17,000 greyscale images of letters A through J, written in a variety of fonts, styles, and handwriting. It contains more variation than the MNIST data, making it a more realistic example for pattern recognition and classification. We will start by using the data to explain how to fit a traditional autoencoder. We will then use the data to explore three applications of autoencoders: dimension reduction, denoising, and anomaly detection.

Finally, before we fit the model, we transform the array a final time. Now might be a good time to talk about the structure of the data. The data is currently stored as a multidimensional array: the first dimension represents the number of images, and the following dimensions represent the height and width (in pixels) of the images.As of right now, the dimensions of the training data are 12951 x 28 x 28, so based off what we just discussed what might these numbers correspond to? (# of images, #pixels in height, #pixels in width :) )

Now, we use array reshape to reshape the arrays into the format that we can input into the neural network. This flattens each image in the arrays into a one-dimensional array (a single row with a number of columns equal to the total number of pixels).

Again, this done because our autenconder expects a one dimensional input.

input_size<- dim(xtrain)[2] * dim(xtrain)[3] #total number of pixels in image

# Reshape the training and testing data:

# Reshape the training data (xtrain) by keeping the number of images as the first dimension
# and setting the second dimension to be equal to the total number of pixels (input_size, defined earlier)
x_train = array_reshape(xtrain, dim=c(dim(xtrain)[1], input_size))

# Print the dimensions of the reshaped training data (x_train) for verification
dim(x_train)
## [1] 12951   784
# Reshape the testing data (xtest) in the same manner as the training data
x_test = array_reshape(xtest, dim=c(dim(xtest)[1], input_size))

# Print the dimensions of the reshaped testing data (x_test) for verification
dim(x_test)
## [1] 4318  784
rm(xtrain)

After printing the dimensions we see that we now have an array whose dimensions correspond to 1) the number of images in each set, and 2) the total number of pixels in each image. This is the final format that we will use as input for the autoencoder.

Now that we have our data in the two dimensional array format, we can start defining the architecture of the model. The input layer of the autoencoder should be as many pixels as there are in the images. Here, the images are 28 pixels long and 28 pixels wide. Thus, our input layer should have 28*28, or 784, nodes. For this initial demonstration, we will be building an autoencoder with a very simple architecture; we will be building a symmetrical autoencoder (i.e.the architecture of the encoder is the mirror image of the decoder). The encoder will have a 784 node input layer, 256-node hidden layer, followed by another hidden layer with 128 nodes, and a final 10 node latent or bottleneck layer.

knitr::include_graphics("all_layers.png")

The idea behind having a 10 node middle layer is to be able to pull out the lower dimensional representation of the data and see if it corresponds to the 10 letters. It likely will notthis may help build intuition about why people call neural networks black boxes. The way a human brain might create groupings may not be the way a neural network creates groupings. However, by having a solid understanding of the mechanical underpinnings, we can hopefully understand why it might be difficult to make sense of the hidden layers while maintaining faith in the output.

set.seed(0417)
latent_size<- 10 #this is the size of the bottleneck
#ENCODER
#define input layer:
enc_input<-layer_input(shape=c(input_size)) #our input is the 28x28 pixels

#define other layers in encoder:
enc_output = enc_input %>% #first layer with pixels 
  layer_dense(units=256, activation = "relu") %>% #hidden layer of the encoder 
  layer_activation_leaky_relu() %>% #leaky relu prevents "dying nodes"
  layer_dense(units=128, activation = "relu") %>% #hidden layer of the encoder 
  layer_activation_leaky_relu() %>% 
  layer_dense(units=latent_size) %>% # "bottleneck" layer. 
  layer_activation_leaky_relu()

encoder = keras_model(enc_input, enc_output)
summary(encoder)
## Model: "model"
## ________________________________________________________________________________
##  Layer (type)                       Output Shape                    Param #     
## ================================================================================
##  input_1 (InputLayer)               [(None, 784)]                   0           
##  dense_2 (Dense)                    (None, 256)                     200960      
##  leaky_re_lu_2 (LeakyReLU)          (None, 256)                     0           
##  dense_1 (Dense)                    (None, 128)                     32896       
##  leaky_re_lu_1 (LeakyReLU)          (None, 128)                     0           
##  dense (Dense)                      (None, 10)                      1290        
##  leaky_re_lu (LeakyReLU)            (None, 10)                      0           
## ================================================================================
## Total params: 235,146
## Trainable params: 235,146
## Non-trainable params: 0
## ________________________________________________________________________________

Printing the summary of the encoder can help us continue to build intuition about what auto encoders and neural networks at large look like. Again, we see that each layer is made up of the nodes we discussed before. Next, we are creating a dense fully connected neural network. This means that each node in layer 1 (input_4 above) is connected to each node in layer 2 (dense_10 above). Additionally, each node in layer 2 has a bias term that is associated with it. Thus for one node in layer 2, there are an associated 784 weights and 1 bias term. Since there 256 nodes in layer 2, we should have 785*256=200660 trainable parameters for layer 2. This is what we see above. Sanity check complete!

Next, using much the same code, we create the decoder. Again, remember that this will have the mirror image architecture of the encoder.

set.seed(0417)
dec_input = layer_input(shape = latent_size) #our input is that latent/bottle neck size

dec_output = dec_input %>% 
  layer_dense(units=128, activation = "relu") %>% 
  layer_activation_leaky_relu() %>% 
  layer_dense(units=256, activation = "relu") %>% 
  layer_activation_leaky_relu() %>% 
  layer_dense(units = input_size, activation = "sigmoid") %>%  #our output is the original input, and sigmoid b/c forces output to be between 0 and 1
  layer_activation_leaky_relu()

decoder = keras_model(dec_input, dec_output)
 
summary(decoder)
## Model: "model_1"
## ________________________________________________________________________________
##  Layer (type)                       Output Shape                    Param #     
## ================================================================================
##  input_2 (InputLayer)               [(None, 10)]                    0           
##  dense_5 (Dense)                    (None, 128)                     1408        
##  leaky_re_lu_5 (LeakyReLU)          (None, 128)                     0           
##  dense_4 (Dense)                    (None, 256)                     33024       
##  leaky_re_lu_4 (LeakyReLU)          (None, 256)                     0           
##  dense_3 (Dense)                    (None, 784)                     201488      
##  leaky_re_lu_3 (LeakyReLU)          (None, 784)                     0           
## ================================================================================
## Total params: 235,920
## Trainable params: 235,920
## Non-trainable params: 0
## ________________________________________________________________________________

Now that we have coded the encoder and decoder, we are ready to combine them.

aen_input = layer_input(shape = input_size) #original input: 28x28

aen_output = aen_input %>% #original input
  encoder() %>%  #encoder
  decoder() #decoder
   
aen = keras_model(aen_input, aen_output)
summary(aen)
## Model: "model_2"
## ________________________________________________________________________________
##  Layer (type)                       Output Shape                    Param #     
## ================================================================================
##  input_3 (InputLayer)               [(None, 784)]                   0           
##  model (Functional)                 (None, 10)                      235146      
##  model_1 (Functional)               (None, 784)                     235920      
## ================================================================================
## Total params: 471,066
## Trainable params: 471,066
## Non-trainable params: 0
## ________________________________________________________________________________

Again, above we simply create a network that combines the encoder and decoder. The total number of parameters is equal to the sum of trainable parameters in the encoder and the decoder. In total, there are 471,066 trainable parameters. Thank goodness for computers, right? We are ready to fit our autoencoder.

Each weight and bias (parameter) is initialized randomly. What happens next is that using these random parameters, the neural network takes the 784 input pixels, repeatedly takes their weighted sum according to the parameters and returns the final transformed output. Here, the goal of the neural network is to take the input, take it to a lower dimension, then return to the original dimension. Thus, the y variable is actually the input. As you may guess, since the weights and biases were initialized randomly, the output will not look anything like the input! This difference between the original input and the output is how we will know that we have to update the weights and biases. The larger the difference, the worse the network did, the more we have to change.

Here, the difference is measured using binary cross entropy. Binary cross entropy is a commonly used loss function (read way of quantifying the difference between our predicted output and the true output) in classification tasks where the output is expected to be a value between 0 and 1.

Given a set of true binary labels y (where y can be either 0 or 1) and the predicted probabilities p for each pixel, the binary cross-entropy loss is calculated as follows:

BinaryCrossEntropy(y, p) = -[y * log(p) + (1 - y) * log(1 - p)]

This loss function has the following characteristics:

  • When the true value is close to the predicted value the loss will be close to 0, which indicates a good prediction.
  • When the true value is far from the predicted value, the loss will be close to 1, indicating a poor prediction.

So, putting this all into context, we would like our model to have a binary cross entropy value as close to 0 as possible. If the value of the loss function is closer to 1, we would like to change our weights and biases to get closer to 0. Thus, we have an optimization problem on our hands: how do we change the weights and biases to minimize the value of the loss function? We calculate the desired change in the weights and biases using back propagation. Although we will not go into the details of back propagation here, a good high-level discussion and visualization can be found here [link to three blue one brown backprop].

> talk about adam > talk about batch size

Thus, we are ready to fit our network to minimize the difference between the output layer and the input layer all while passing through a lower dimension.

#Fitting the model
aen %>% compile(
  optimizer = 'adam',  #note that the website used rmsprop instead, could choose either
  loss = 'binary_crossentropy', 
)

#Train the model:
aen %>% fit(x= x_train,
            y= x_train,  #b/c in autoencoders, goal is to reconstruct input
            epochs=50, #number of times we feed forward and use backprop to change the weights and biases
            batch_size=256)

Now the autoencoder has been fit :). The next step is to see how it does taking unseen images of letters to a lower dimension and then reconstructing them.

First, we encode the 4,318 images in the test data.

encoded_imgs <- encoder %>% 
                predict(x_test)

The output is 4,318*10. Next, we pass these through the decoder.

#decoder
decoded_imgs<- decoder %>%
               predict(encoded_imgs) #predicting on the output of the encoder

Now that we have the decoded images, the final step is to convert it to 4318 * 28 *28 again so that we can plot them and see how we did.

#change shape of the decoded data: back to 10,000 x 28 x 28, currently 10,000 x 784
pred_images = array_reshape(decoded_imgs, dim=c(dim(decoded_imgs)[1], 28, 28))
op <- par(mfrow=c(10,2), mar=c(1,0,0,0)) #setup: 12 images in each of 2 columns
letters_to_test<- c(1,567,2876,1888,960,4000)

#loop through 1-10:
for (i in letters_to_test){
  plot(as.raster(xtest[i,,]))
    plot(as.raster(pred_images[i,,]))
}

On the right, we have the original images, and on the left we have the reconstructed images. We can see that the network doesnt do great when there are thin little lines. But, for the most part, its not awful!

Anomaly Detection Anomaly Detection in not-mnist Now we will demonstrate the usefulness of autoencoders for anomaly detection.

This is done by first calculating the reconstruction error by comparing the output to the input. Then, we select the top 0.001% of anomalous inputs and look at them.

reconstruction_errors <- apply(X = x_test - decoded_imgs, MARGIN = 1, FUN = function(x) sqrt(sum(x^2)))
threshold <- quantile(reconstruction_errors, probs = 0.999)
# Step 3: Identify the indices of the images with reconstruction errors greater than the threshold value
anomaly_indices <- which(reconstruction_errors > threshold)
op <- par(mfrow=c(10,2), mar=c(1,0,0,0)) #setup: 12 images in each of 2 columns
#loop through 1-10:
for (i in anomaly_indices){
  plot(as.raster(xtest[i,,]))
    plot(as.raster(pred_images[i,,]))
}

The original inputs on the right look pretty weird to us! According to the autoencoder the images on the right are the top five weirdest.

anomaly detection with mnist

#load mnist 
mnist <- dataset_mnist()
X_train <- mnist$train$x
X_test <- mnist$test$x
y_train <- mnist$train$y
y_test <- mnist$test$y
#doesn't matter which we use (train vs. test), and we don't need the y's since we aren't actually doing classification 
#so I'm just going to select 10 images from X_train

x_mnist<- X_train[1:10, , ] #select images 

x_mnist = array_reshape(x_mnist, dim=c(dim(x_mnist)[1], 784)) #reshape the 10 images 

rm(mnist, X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test) #remove the rest of the data

Now that we have the mnist data in the correct format, we add it to the x_test data. The idea is that now we will have the original test letter data with an additional ten images of numbers. We would hope that the greatest reconstruction error is on the number images and thus identified.

with_mnist<- abind(x_test,x_mnist, along=1)
encoded_with_mnist <- encoder %>% 
                predict(with_mnist)
decoded_with_mnist<- decoder %>%
               predict(encoded_with_mnist)

mnist_reconstruction_errors <- apply(X = with_mnist - decoded_with_mnist, MARGIN = 1, FUN = function(x) sqrt(sum(x^2)))
mnist_threshold <- quantile(mnist_reconstruction_errors, probs = 0.999)
# Step 3: Identify the indices of the images with reconstruction errors greater than the threshold value
mnist_anomaly_indices <- which(mnist_reconstruction_errors > mnist_threshold)

mnist_pred_images = array_reshape(decoded_with_mnist, dim=c(dim(decoded_with_mnist)[1], 28, 28))
with_mnist_2 = array_reshape(with_mnist, dim=c(dim(with_mnist)[1], 28, 28))

normalized_with_mnist_2 <- with_mnist_2 / max(with_mnist_2)
normalized_mnist_pred_images <- mnist_pred_images / max(mnist_pred_images)

op <- par(mfrow=c(10,2), mar=c(1,0,0,0)) #setup: 12 images in each of 2 columns
#loop through 1-10:
for (i in mnist_anomaly_indices){
  plot(as.raster(normalized_with_mnist_2[i,,]))
  plot(as.raster(normalized_mnist_pred_images[i,,]))
}

denoising

Another application of autoencoders is for denoising. To do this, lets first corrupt the images that we tested above. This will be done by randomly setting 20% of the pixels in the input to 0.

set.seed(0417)
corrupt_image<- function (input){
  res_mat<- matrix(NA, nrow=nrow(input), ncol=784)
  for (i in 1:nrow(input)){
    pixels_to_corrupt<- sample(1:784, .4*(784), replace = FALSE)
    pixel_to_corrupt_1<- sample(pixels_to_corrupt, .5*0.4*784, replace = FALSE)
    pixel_to_corrupt_0<- pixels_to_corrupt[-pixel_to_corrupt_1]

  for(j in 1:784){
    if(j %in% pixel_to_corrupt_0){res_mat[i,j]<- 0}
    else if (j %in% pixel_to_corrupt_1){res_mat[i,j]<- 1}
    else{res_mat[i,j]<- input[i,j]}
    }
  }
  return(res_mat)
}

x_train_corrupt<- corrupt_image(x_train)
x_test_corrupt<- corrupt_image(x_test)

Now that we have corrupted the images, we can go ahead and pass them though the autoencoder and compare the output to the corrupted input! > add the piece about how we fit the autoencoder with the corrupted images as the x and the non-corrupted images as the y. Maybe cite the paper that talks about how these might be mathematically equivalent.

  optimizer = 'adam',  #note that the website used rmsprop instead, could choose either
  loss = 'binary_crossentropy', #the website used binary_crossentropy
)

#Train the model:
aen %>% fit(x= x_train_corrupt,
            y= x_train,  #b/c in autoencoders, goal is to reconstruct input
            epochs=50, #number of times we feed forward and use backprop to change the weights and biases
            batch_size=256)
encoded_corrupted_imgs <- encoder %>% 
                predict(x_test_corrupt)
decoded_corrupted_imgs<- decoder %>%
               predict(encoded_corrupted_imgs)
pred_corrupted_images = array_reshape(decoded_corrupted_imgs, dim=c(dim(decoded_corrupted_imgs)[1], 28, 28))
corrupted_images = array_reshape(x_test_corrupt, dim=c(dim(x_test_corrupt)[1], 28, 28))

op <- par(mfrow=c(10,2), mar=c(1,0,0,0)) #setup: 12 images in each of 2 columns
#loop through 1-10:
for (i in letters_to_test){
  plot(as.raster(corrupted_images[i,,]))
    plot(as.raster(pred_corrupted_images[i,,]))
}

Above, we can see that the noise we introduced has been removed from the images :)
